# GxP Execution

Execution is split into clearly separated phases. Only the controlled phases are GxP.

## Phases

| Phase | GxP? | Repeatable | Generates deviation? |
|---|---|---|---|
| Dry-run | No (preparatory) | Yes, unlimited | **Never** |
| Pre-requisites | **Yes** | No (controlled) | **Yes** |
| Run / Install | **Yes** | No (controlled) | **Yes** |

## Dry-run (preparatory)

- A **complete dry-run is mandatory before any GxP run** (pre-requisites or run/install).
- The dry-run MUST be **documented** (expected actions, inputs, environment) and **automated** (a `--dry-run` flag or `dry_run: true` workflow input — not a manual ad-hoc procedure).
- Every dry-run artifact — logs, console output, reports, tickets — MUST be **clearly labelled as dry-run** (e.g. each action prefixed `[dry-run] would ...`, report header `MODE: DRY-RUN`).
- A dry-run produces **no GxP record and no deviation**, regardless of how many times it is run.
- A dry-run MUST NOT mutate any controlled system, dataset, or environment.

## Pre-requisites (GxP)

- Treated as a **controlled GxP step**: capture who/what/when, versions, and checks performed.
- Any unmet pre-requisite or unexpected result is an **anomaly → open a deviation** with traceability (cause, impact, resolution, approval).

## Run / Install (GxP)

- Treated as a **controlled GxP step**, executed only after a successful, labelled dry-run.
- Any failure, partial result, or out-of-spec behaviour is an **anomaly → open a deviation**; do not silently retry.
- Record the executed version, environment, operator, and evidence (logs, hashes).

## Deviations

- Deviations are raised **only** by GxP phases (pre-requisites, run/install) — **never** by dry-runs.
- Each deviation MUST be traceable: description, root cause, impact, corrective action, and the Git commit or ticket reference.

## Evidence and traceability

- Keep Git as the source of truth for dry-run documentation, GxP run evidence, and deviations.
- Use the `gxp-unit-test-report-generator` skill for audit-ready report format (CFR 21 Part 11 traceability).
